to drugs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute tubulointerstitial nephritis","Direct tubular toxicity","Glomerular inflammation","Pre-renal ischaemia","Tubular crystal deposition"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute tubulointerstitial nephritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically results from drug-induced hypersensitivity reactions. The immune response involves both type I (immediate) and type IV (delayed) hypersensitivity mechanisms, with inflammatory infiltrates in the renal interstitium. Common causative medications include penicillins, sulfonamides, and proton pump inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect tubular toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E occurs through dose-dependent injury to tubular cells, as seen with aminoglycosides and contrast media\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlomerular inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with autoimmune conditions rather than drug reactions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPre-renal ischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E results from reduced renal perfusion due to volume depletion or altered haemodynamics\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETubular crystal deposition\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with medications that precipitate within tubules, such as aciclovir or methotrexate\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of drug-induced acute tubulointerstitial nephritis is suggested by the presence of fever, rash, and eosinophilia, though these classic findings are not always present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute tubulointerstitial nephritis is commonly caused by type I (immediate) and type IV (delayed) hypersensitivity reactions to medications","Common medications causing acute tubulointerstitial nephritis include penicillins, sulfonamides, and proton pump inhibitors","Drug-induced acute tubulointerstitial nephritis is characterized by inflammatory infiltrates in the renal interstitium"],"references":["Perazella MA, Rosner MH. Drug-Induced Acute Kidney Injury. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2022 Aug;17(8):1220-1233. doi: 10.2215/CJN.11290821. Epub 2022 Mar 10. PMID: 35273009; PMCID: PMC9435983.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52645"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15034"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52645"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T22:49:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T22:50:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7722"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67189"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.em